To understand it, you just need to memorize the golden rule of data flow: Covariance is for data coming OUT. Contravariance is for data going IN.

1. Covariance (out keyword)

Covariance allows you to use a more derived (more specific) type than the generic parameter originally specified. It preserves the normal direction of inheritance.

In C#, you declare a generic type parameter as covariant using the out keyword (e.g., IEnumerable<out T>). This tells the compiler: "This type parameter will ONLY ever be returned as an output. It will never be passed in as a parameter."

Why is it safe?
If you have a collection of strings, it is completely safe to read them and treat them as objects, because every string is an object.

// IEnumerable is covariant: public interface IEnumerable<out T>

IEnumerable<string> strings = new List<string> { "Hello", "World" };

// COVARIANCE: We can safely assign an IEnumerable<string> to an IEnumerable<object>
// because we are only pulling data OUT of the sequence.
IEnumerable<object> objects = strings; 

foreach (object obj in objects)
{
    Console.WriteLine(obj); // Perfectly safe!
}

Just like the last example, we can see exactly why the compiler enforces the rules by trying to break them.

If you try to cheat and use a covariant type parameter (out T) for data going IN (like a method parameter), your application's type safety falls apart.

Here is the exact scenario showing why you can only use out T for return values, and how things go catastrophically wrong if you use it for inputs.

We will use the exact same inheritance hierarchy:

C#
public class Animal { }
public class Dog : Animal { }
public class Cat : Animal { }
Now, we create a hypothetical interface. We will mark T as covariant using the out keyword, but we will break the rules by trying to accept T as an input parameter.

C#
// HYPOTHETICAL: Imagine the compiler allowed this
public interface IContainer<out T>
{
    T GetItem();          // ✅ Legal: Data coming OUT
    void AddItem(T item); // ❌ COMPILER ERROR: Data going IN
}
2. The Counter-Example (Why it breaks)
Why does the compiler block void AddItem(T item)? Let's pretend it didn't, and you implemented a container specifically for dogs.

C#
public class DogContainer : IContainer<Dog>
{
    private List<Dog> _dogs = new List<Dog>();

    public Dog GetItem() => _dogs.First();
    
    // Because this is a DogContainer, it strictly accepts Dogs.
    public void AddItem(Dog item) 
    {
        _dogs.Add(item); 
    }
}
Now, we use covariance in our main code. Covariance allows us to take a specific container (DogContainer) and assign it to a more generic variable (IContainer<Animal>).

C#
// 1. Covariance in action: Assigning Dog to Animal.
// The compiler says: "A container that outputs Dogs can safely be treated as a container that outputs Animals."
IContainer<Animal> animalContainer = new DogContainer();

// 2. We call the method to put an item IN.
// Because the variable is IContainer<Animal>, C# thinks it's perfectly legal to add a Cat.
animalContainer.AddItem(new Cat()); 
3. The Fatal Crash
Look at that last line: animalContainer.AddItem(new Cat());

The variable animalContainer expects that you can put any Animal inside it.

So, you pass it a Cat.

But the underlying object in memory is actually a DogContainer.

The DogContainer.AddItem() method is expecting a Dog.

If the compiler had allowed this, you would have just successfully shoved a Cat into a List<Dog>. The next time another part of your code looped through that DogContainer and called dog.Bark(), your application would crash because one of those dogs is secretly a cat.

By forcing out T to only ever be used for return types, the compiler guarantees you can never push the wrong data into the object.


4. The Real-World "Oops": C# Arrays

Interestingly, you do not have to use your imagination to see this crash happen in the real world.

When C# 1.0 was created (long before Generics existed), Microsoft decided to make standard arrays covariant so that developers could write helper methods that accepted object[] and passed string[] into them.

Because arrays are covariant but allow data to go IN and OUT, this exact crash is actually legal to compile in C# today:

C#
// 1. Create an array of strings (Strings are Objects)
string[] strings = new string[5];

// 2. Covariance allows us to assign it to an object array
object[] objects = strings;

// 3. We put an integer IN to the object array (Integers are Objects)
// COMPILES PERFECTLY FINE!
objects[0] = 42; 

// 4. RUNTIME CRASH: ArrayTypeMismatchException!
// The CLR realizes you just tried to shove an int into a string array.
This array behavior is universally considered a historical mistake in the design of C#. When Microsoft introduced Generics in C# 2.0 (and the in/out keywords in C# 4.0), they fixed this mistake by strictly enforcing the In/Out rules for all new interfaces and delegates.


2. Contravariance (in keyword)

Contravariance is the exact opposite. It allows you to use a less derived (more generic) type than originally specified. It reverses the normal direction of inheritance.

In C#, you declare a generic type parameter as contravariant using the in keyword (e.g., Action<in T>). This tells the compiler: "This type parameter will ONLY ever be accepted as an input parameter. It will never be returned."

// Action is contravariant: public delegate void Action<in T>(T obj)

// A method that can handle ANY object
Action<object> printObject = (object obj) => Console.WriteLine(obj.GetType());

// CONTRAVARIANCE: We can safely assign an Action<object> to an Action<string>
// because a method that accepts ANY object can safely accept a string.
Action<string> printString = printObject;

// We are passing data IN.
printString("Hello World");



A counter-example is the absolute best way to understand why C# enforces strict rules around contravariance.
If you try to cheat the system and use a contravariant type parameter (in T) for data coming OUT (like a method return type), the compiler will immediately throw an error.

Here is the exact scenario showing why the compiler must stop you, and how your application would catastrophically crash if it didn't.

Let's define a simple inheritance hierarchy:

C#
public class Animal { }
public class Dog : Animal { }
public class Cat : Animal { }


Now, let's create a hypothetical interface. We will mark T as contravariant using the in keyword, but we will break the rules by trying to use T as a return type (data coming OUT).

C#
// HYPOTHETICAL: Imagine the compiler allowed this
public interface IProcessor<in T>
{
    void Process(T item); // ✅ Legal: Data going IN
    T GetItem();          // ❌ COMPILER ERROR: Data coming OUT
}

2. The Counter-Example (Why it breaks)

Why does the compiler block T GetItem()? Let's pretend for a moment that the C# compiler allowed it. Here is how you would accidentally destroy the type safety of your application.

First, you implement the interface for a generic Animal.

C#
public class AnimalProcessor : IProcessor<Animal>
{
    public void Process(Animal item) { /* do something */ }
    
    // Because this processes generic animals, 
    // it's perfectly legal for it to return a Cat.
    public Animal GetItem() 
    {
        return new Cat(); 
    }
}
Now, we use contravariance in our main code. Contravariance allows us to assign a generic processor (Animal) to a more specific variable (Dog).

C#
// 1. Contravariance in action: Assigning Animal to Dog.
// The compiler says "A processor that can handle ANY animal can handle a Dog."
IProcessor<Dog> dogProcessor = new AnimalProcessor();

// 2. We call the method to get our item out.
// Because the variable is IProcessor<Dog>, C# expects GetItem() to return a Dog.
Dog myDog = dogProcessor.GetItem(); 
3. The Fatal Crash
Look closely at that last line: Dog myDog = dogProcessor.GetItem();

The variable is expecting a Dog.

But the underlying object is an AnimalProcessor.

The AnimalProcessor.GetItem() method actually returns a Cat.

If the compiler had allowed this, you would have just successfully stuffed a Cat into a Dog variable. The moment you tried to call myDog.Bark(), your entire application would suffer a fatal runtime crash.

The Takeaway
By forcing you to use the in keyword, the C# compiler guarantees that contravariant types can only ever consume data, never produce it. Because AnimalProcessor is never allowed to return data, it is mathematically impossible for it to accidentally hand you a Cat when you asked for a Dog.



3. Invariance (Neither in nor out)

If a generic interface or delegate takes data IN and passes data OUT, it cannot be variant at all. It is strictly Invariant. The types must match exactly.

The classic example is IList<T>.

C#
IList<string> strings = new List<string>();

// ERROR: Cannot implicitly convert type 'IList<string>' to 'IList<object>'
IList<object> objects = strings;

Why does the compiler block this?

Imagine if the compiler allowed that assignment. Because objects is an IList<object>, it has an .Add(object) method. You could do this:

objects.Add(new DateTime(2025, 1, 1)); // Add a date to the object list

But remember, objects is actually pointing to strings in memory! You would have just successfully stuffed a DateTime into a List<string>, completely breaking the type safety of C# and causing a runtime crash.

By forcing IList<T> to be invariant, C# protects you from this scenario.

